Part life-coach, part Machiavelli, part Yoda, Balthasar Gracian
\[1601-1658\], a Jesuit priest, wrote this collection of pithy sayings
four centuries ago. Gracian speaks to the twenty-first century as well
as the seventeenth. It's only a matter of time before someone markets
Gracian's life advice to busy executives, like Sun Tzu or the Book of
Five Rings (if it hasn't been already). In the meantime, Gracian can be
our little secret.

Jacobs, the translator, is also the author of many books of folklore,
etexts of which can also be found at this site, for instance, [Celtic
Fairy Tales](../../neu/celt/cft/index.md), [English Fairy
Tales](../../neu/eng/eft/index.md), and [Indian Fairy
Tales](../../hin/ift/index.md).

Production note: I have arbitrarily divided the body of the translation
into files of 50 sayings each: Jacobs recommended reading the book 50
sayings at a time.

